INSERT INTO `wp_postmeta` VALUES (81,3534,'drill_type_information','<strong>We focus on use of both the left hand and the right hand, practicing the crossover, inside out, reverse dribble, around the back, between the legs, step back, slide dribble, power dribble, and speed dribble.</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>Dribble moving the elbow and wrist through the ball, no higher than the thigh, hips down / eyes up.</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong><em>“Break the Floor” </em>with your dribble. When you dribble hard the ball returns quickly. This is especially important when shooting off the dribble. A hard dribble can be snapped into the shot pocket more quickly than a soft dribble.</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong> Emphasis is on attacking at proper angles. If the dribble attack is too wide the defender can easily recover. Avoid turning the shoulders. Attack the ankles and hand of the defender. As you step past the defender, dribbling with the hand farthest from the defender, the inside hand leads through – like shaking hands – maintaining body position and shielding the ball from the reach of the defender.</strong>\r\n\r\n<img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-3532\" src=\"http://one-voice-basketball.local/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/becky-dribble-227x300.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"311\" height=\"411\" />\r\n\r\n<strong>Shift speeds – slow, fast, pull back, fast.</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>The low man wins – get your shoulder to the defender’s hip, off hand is near the floor – turn the corner and seal the defender with your body.</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>Change the defender’s lead foot. A jab can make the defender move, opening up the jump shot or the blow by with the dribble.</strong>\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-3533\" src=\"http://one-voice-basketball.local/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/liv-arm-bar-300x240.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"240\" />\r\n\r\n<strong>I know, I know, I’ve already said this but… PLAYERS MUST DEVELOP GOOD COURT VISION. Improving your handle is great but if you miss an open teammate or an open path to the hoop you’re missing an opportunity to help your team. Learn to dribble with your eyes up!  To be clear, even the pros occasionally look down, especially when dribbling in high traffic areas, but they quickly scan the court utilizing their peripheral vision.</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>Improving your handle is great but, if you miss an open teammate or an open path to the hoop because your eyes are down rather than on the rim, then you are missing an opportunity to help your team. Learn to dribble with your eyes up!</strong>');
INSERT INTO `wp_postmeta` VALUES (82,3534,'_drill_type_information','field_5c257785f6ad7');
INSERT INTO `wp_postmeta` VALUES (83,3534,'warm_up_exercises','<strong>BALL SLAPS – WARM UP   (I)</strong>\r\n\r\nSlap the ball with the right hand for 15 seconds then the left hand – warms up the hands.\r\n\r\n<strong>POUND DRIBBLES   (I) </strong>  <strong><em>warm up, ball control</em></strong>\r\n\r\nStand in a power dribble stance, the ball at the back foot.  Pound dribble for 30 seconds, no higher than the knee. Switch to the left hand. EYES UP – TO THE RIM.\r\n\r\n<strong>BALL WRAPS (I)</strong>   <strong><em>warm up, fingertip control</em></strong>\r\n\r\nWrap the ball around the knees, head, waist – 15 seconds then change direction. Add figure eights forward and backward.');
INSERT INTO `wp_postmeta` VALUES (84,3534,'_warm_up_exercises','field_5c25729f3fd1e');
