INSERT INTO `wp_postmeta` VALUES (340,3586,'drill_type_information','As the level of competition improves players will need to understand the value of space and spacing on the court. The offensive player needs to create space - from the defender(s) to make a pass, to shoot, to escape a trapping defense etc. The defensive player must work to reduce the space the offensive player has – to make passing more difficult, to contest shots, to successfully trap and create turnovers etc.\r\n\r\nOffensive space can be created in a number of ways. The design and execution of the offensive philosophy is the simplest way to create space. Adopting an offensive philosophy that maximizes the talent you have is essential. Properly executed, that philosophy will put your players in a position on the court where they have the space necessary to use their skills.\r\n\r\nEach developing level of competition requires additional skills sets. Facing effective defensive teams, players will have to use other tactics to maximize the benefits of their offensive philosophy. These tactics include...\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li>Effectively using screens to create space</li>\r\n 	<li>Moving with a purpose</li>\r\n 	<li>Using a variety of effective cuts and curls</li>\r\n 	<li>Maintaining proper spacing to make it more difficult to defend and support “on the ball” defenders</li>\r\n 	<li>Using proper footwork and balance to efficiently use the space available</li>\r\n 	<li>Developing fundamental moves with and without the ball</li>\r\n 	<li>Accurate and timely passing</li>\r\n 	<li>Making the extra pass to defeat defensive pressure</li>\r\n 	<li>Changing speeds and changing direction skills</li>\r\n 	<li>Dribbling / ball handling skills</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nGetting separation or creating space requires a proper stance, ball protection, setting proper angles, and efficiency. You must create a variety of strategies to assure that you can to get separation with one bounce.\r\n\r\nLearn to get separation -\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li>Off the catch</li>\r\n 	<li>Using the dribble</li>\r\n 	<li>On the finish.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong>EVERY TIME YOU CATCH THE BALL AND SQUARE  / FACE UP</strong> –\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li>Bring your eyes to the rim.</li>\r\n 	<li>Allow your peripheral vision to read the situation.</li>\r\n 	<li>If the defender’s hands are down – shoot (if you are in your range and there is not a better option – like passing to an open teammate).</li>\r\n 	<li>If the defender’s hands are up - attack the top hand. This is just like attacking the top foot (the top hand will also be the top foot)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong>COMPOUND MOVES</strong>\r\n\r\nUse a combination of the various moves to create space. Against a tight defender the first move may be soft, followed by a sharper move. Work on changing speeds and changing direction.  As you approach the defender change direction then go right at the defender and make another move, changing direction again. A good defender will be able to defend the first move. An effective offensive player learns to develop a counter moves in order to beat her defender.\r\n\r\n<strong>3 Ways to Make Space</strong>\r\n\r\nCreate space – step back.\r\n\r\nClaim space – bump off a post move\r\n\r\nKeep space – once space is created keep it by using footwork to maintain');
